04054nam a22006135i 9780226495408DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017022086  a9780226495408  a(DE-B1597)522579  a(OCoLC)1011497374  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK2295.S6bA43 2018 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a324.2730975bA4262231 aAldrich, John H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Parties Matter :bPolitical Competition and Democracy in the American South /cJohn H. Aldrich, John D. Griffin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b72 halftones, 17 line drawings, 20 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tPart One. Why Parties Matter -- tPart Two. The Exceptional South -- tPart Three. The Democratic Fruits of Party Competition -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the founding of the American Republic, the North and South have followed remarkably different paths of political development. Among the factors that have led to their divergence throughout much of history are differences in the levels of competition among the political parties. While the North has generally enjoyed a well-defined two-party system, the South has tended to have only weakly developed political parties—and at times no system of parties to speak of. With Why Parties Matter, John H. Aldrich and John D. Griffin make a compelling case that competition between political parties is an essential component of a democracy that is responsive to its citizens and thus able to address their concerns. Tracing the history of the parties through four eras—the Democratic-Whig party era that preceded the Civil War; the post-Reconstruction period; the Jim Crow era, when competition between the parties virtually disappeared; and the modern era—Aldrich and Griffin show how and when competition emerged between the parties and the conditions under which it succeeded and failed. In the modern era, as party competition in the South has come to be widely regarded as matching that of the North, the authors conclude by exploring the question of whether the South is poised to become a one-party system once again with the Republican party now dominant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDemocracyzSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aElectionszSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical partieszSouthern StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acompetition.  ademocracy.  ahistory.  aparties.  arepresentation.  asouth.1 aGriffin, John D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022649523140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226495408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226495408/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles